Dear Eva, I've watched nearly all of your videos over the last week or so and I really like the content that you create and provide - thank you for that, really!
I also recognised the more "critical" scenes you did here and there, e.g. mentioning the power of different passports or discussing your privilege of being a Western/white woman.
My very personal perception is that, as a travel vlogger who started doing this within the last few years, as someone who is following their dreams and wants to make a living out of it, you will probably want to refrain from criticism, especially when you are collaborating with different brands and governments as you obviously did here in Pakistan. Of course, that is perfectly fine and reasonable, but I have to say, it does take away from the things you say here in this video, for example. I have absolutely no doubt about the positive things you say and I would go to Pakistan in an instant, but the things you say here about modest dresscodes, patriachal structures, etc. sound very streamlined and euphemistic to my ears. I wonder if you have told your friends more in depth about your experiences than what you share here, where you are obviously making advertising for the Pakistani tourism industry. Of course there are strong women everywhere, even in very conservative countries, but that doesn't say anything about the structural problem or how you as a woman felt while being there. Were you traveling alone also, without guides? Where you told where to go and what to see? Were you able to go wherever you wanted to? Were you able to ask critical questions and still be welcome?

You are asking in your video why would Pakistan not become the next #1 travel destination for a summer trip - well, you say it in your video - can you imagine the stereotypical summer tourist wearing a long sleeved swim suit during the day and partying without alcohol in the evenings? I guess that is why they go to Mallorca :)

For example, the disclaimer you gave with your Saudi videos made your content so much more trustworthy. From what you said and what your Saudi friends said, I feel like I got a good idea of what it would be like to travel there as a solo woman. From your Pakistan videos, I did enjoy the entertainment and the beauty of your videos, but I see them like I see advertising and I don't turn to advertising for critical information.

Anyway, that's just what I had to say after watching nearly every single one of your videos. Thanks and, after looking at your Instagram, please do also share your mid-pandemic adventures from Poland with us, we are curious :) have a good day!

@Andreea Boloca Well, you need to go to Pakistan. The first time you go you'll get a one year multiple entry visa.
Once you arrive in Pakistan, go to NADRA with your husband, it's the organization in Pakistan that issues ID cards.
Apply for a POC (Pakistan Origin Card).
It's valid for seven years and you can renew it online from anywhere in the world after that.
Next time you go to Pakistan, you don't need a visa. Just take your European passport and your POC. You should be good to go.

Those from India, the process is easier for them. Once in Pakistan, they just need to make a statement, saying I'm Pakistani. They need to give up their Indian nationality and that's it. They can hey a normal Pakistani ID and a normal Pakistani passport. It's because of the history of the two countries. Pakistan gives nationality to anyone who wants to be a Pakistani.

You could do that too, but I believe your European passport should be more valuable. Cheers!

Hi Eva, the Pakistan Govt. plans to ease the visa requirements this year for around 55 countries, including most of Europe, hopefully including the UK. Maybe they'll get rid of the letter of invitation requirement or introduce E visas. I want to visit Lahore and Islamabad in November for 2 weeks, then me and a friend want to do a tour of North Pakistan in June 2020 with Wild Frontiers Travel. Pakistan can be the number one go-to destination in the world if things are made easier for tourists that wish to go there.  With BA flights from LHR to Islamabad resuming this June, an easing of visa requirements and your showcasing the stunning beauty of Pakistan to the world through your vlogs, this can happen.

Hi Terry, as you have said, the bureaucratic procedure related to visa and stuff have been one of the main hurdles in attracting foreign tourists. The previous government was really cautious in handing visas to foreigners on account of presence of foreign spies in the country. Improving security situation was the foremost priority of the government and that's why them taking a conservative approach in issuing visas was perhaps need of the hour. Still, one would think they could have done much more to make the procedure faster and better.
The tourism industry hasn't flourished as much as it should have post 2015/16 security improvement. However, with the change of government we are witnessing a refreshing change in the tourism policy and like you have mentioned, the visa relaxation for dozens of countries is at the heart of that change. From what I read, UK citizens are eligible for E-visa as well as Visa-on-arrival. There might be a few conditions to those visa like booking through a certain group. Even if such conditions are there, I am sure they wouldn't be laborious.
It definitely has the tools and resources to become a top traveling destinations but that would only be possible with the visits of foreign tourists like you. So you should definitely go through with your trip in November. That infact is the ideal time really in terms of weather to visit Lahore, Islamabad or Punjab/Sindh for that matter. I am sure once you return from that trip, you'll be campaigning amongst your peers to give Pakistan a try for their next vacations!
Cheers!
